\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 Carefully remove the zest from the lemons using a microplane or rasp {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/grater/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 grater}}, being careful not to remove any of the white pith. Reserve the lemons to make {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/lemonade/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 lemonade}} or squeeze and freeze the juice for later use.\
Put the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/zest/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 lemon zest}} into a lidded glass container that is at least 2-quarts in size. Pour the vodka over the zest, and let sit in a cool dark place for 7 days.\
After 7 days, strain the liquid through a fine mesh {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/strainer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 strainer}} lined with muslin or several layers of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cheesecloth/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cheesecloth}} and return the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/vodka/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 vodka}} to the container.\
Combine the water and sugar in a small {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/saucepan/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 saucepan}} set over high heat and cook, stirring continually, until the sugar is completely dissolved, approximately 3 minutes. Once completely cool, add the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/sugar-syrup/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sugar syrup}} to the vodka, and stir to combine.\
Cover and put the container in the freezer for at least 4 hours. Limoncello can be stored in the freezer for up to a year.\
